1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,740
"You have the right to remain silent." You have

2
00:00:02,740 --> 00:00:04,400
heard it in a thousand movies,

3
00:00:04,400 --> 00:00:05,960
and maybe once in real life.

4
00:00:06,620 --> 00:00:09,360
But that sentence was not written by a screenwriter.

5
00:00:09,900 --> 00:00:12,760
It comes from a single confession that the Supreme

6
00:00:12,760 --> 00:00:16,124
Court of the United States refused to allow —

7
00:00:16,125 --> 00:00:18,280
given by a man who won his case at

8
00:00:18,280 --> 00:00:20,620
the highest court in the land and still ended

9
00:00:20,620 --> 00:00:21,580
up back in prison.

10
00:00:22,340 --> 00:00:25,640
This is how four sentences rewrote every arrest in

11
00:00:25,640 --> 00:00:26,040
America.

12
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:33,418
We treat the warning as a courtesy —

13
00:00:33,419 --> 00:00:35,360
a few words an officer mutters while the handcuffs

14
00:00:35,360 --> 00:00:35,960
go on.

15
00:00:36,560 --> 00:00:37,680
It is not a courtesy.

16
00:00:38,440 --> 00:00:39,280
It is a repair.

17
00:00:40,540 --> 00:00:44,120
In 1966, the Supreme Court decided that the real

18
00:00:44,120 --> 00:00:47,620
problem was not any single officer or any single

19
00:00:47,620 --> 00:00:48,060
suspect.

20
00:00:48,780 --> 00:00:52,720
The problem was the interrogation room itself: a closed

21
00:00:52,720 --> 00:00:56,260
space where steady pressure can turn silence into a

22
00:00:56,260 --> 00:00:56,660
confession.

23
00:00:57,580 --> 00:00:59,100
So the Court built a fix,

24
00:00:59,600 --> 00:01:02,020
and it anchored that fix in the Fifth Amendment

25
00:01:02,507 --> 00:01:02,827
—

26
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:05,640
the promise that no person can be forced to

27
00:01:05,640 --> 00:01:07,420
be a witness against themselves.

28
00:01:08,600 --> 00:01:11,500
Over the next twelve minutes: the case that created

29
00:01:11,500 --> 00:01:14,360
the warning, the man whose name it carries,

30
00:01:14,780 --> 00:01:18,080
and why those few words quietly shape every arrest.

31
00:01:18,760 --> 00:01:20,460
It begins in Phoenix, Arizona,

32
00:01:20,460 --> 00:01:21,820
in 1963.

33
00:01:22,720 --> 00:01:25,560
A man named Ernesto Miranda is arrested and taken

34
00:01:25,560 --> 00:01:26,420
in for questioning.

35
00:01:27,080 --> 00:01:29,840
What happens next is, on the surface,

36
00:01:30,280 --> 00:01:31,965
completely ordinary —

37
00:01:32,400 --> 00:01:34,420
and that is exactly why it matters.

38
00:01:35,380 --> 00:01:39,000
He is placed in a room with police and

39
00:01:39,520 --> 00:01:40,080
questioned.

40
00:01:40,081 --> 00:01:41,460
And during that questioning, he confesses.

41
00:01:41,860 --> 00:01:44,100
He is never told that he does not have

42
00:01:44,100 --> 00:01:44,880
to say anything.

43
00:01:45,560 --> 00:01:47,480
He is never told that he could have a

44
00:01:47,480 --> 00:01:48,860
lawyer sitting beside him.

45
00:01:49,560 --> 00:01:51,720
Think about what that room actually is.

46
00:01:52,340 --> 00:01:55,440
On one side: trained investigators who do this every

47
00:01:55,440 --> 00:01:57,380
day, who control the door,

48
00:01:58,080 --> 00:01:59,620
the clock, and the questions.

49
00:02:00,500 --> 00:02:02,620
On the other side: one person,

50
00:02:02,620 --> 00:02:05,780
alone, who may have no idea where the limits

51
00:02:05,780 --> 00:02:06,856
are —

52
00:02:06,857 --> 00:02:09,500
whether he can stop, whether he can wait,

53
00:02:10,100 --> 00:02:11,920
whether anyone is coming to help.

54
00:02:12,780 --> 00:02:15,940
Nothing dramatic has to happen for that imbalance to

55
00:02:15,940 --> 00:02:16,620
do its work.

56
00:02:17,420 --> 00:02:18,680
The room is quiet.

57
00:02:19,260 --> 00:02:20,540
The pressure is patient.

58
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:22,440
And the longer it lasts,

59
00:02:22,560 --> 00:02:25,040
the more natural it feels to fill the silence

60
00:02:26,116 --> 00:02:26,436
—

61
00:02:26,437 --> 00:02:29,500
to explain, to correct, to try to talk your

62
00:02:29,500 --> 00:02:30,160
way out.

63
00:02:30,920 --> 00:02:32,880
That instinct, to keep talking,

64
00:02:33,140 --> 00:02:35,800
is exactly what the room is built to use.

65
00:02:36,480 --> 00:02:37,580
And at the end of it,

66
00:02:37,780 --> 00:02:40,460
the most powerful piece of evidence in the entire

67
00:02:40,460 --> 00:02:45,160
case is something the suspect produced himself: his own

68
00:02:45,160 --> 00:02:45,660
words.

69
00:02:46,300 --> 00:02:49,200
A confession feels like proof beyond argument.

70
00:02:49,840 --> 00:02:52,520
Who would admit to something they did not do?

71
00:02:52,980 --> 00:02:55,320
But the law had started to ask a harder

72
00:02:55,320 --> 00:02:56,927
question —

73
00:02:56,928 --> 00:03:00,060
not "did he say it?" but "did he know

74
00:03:00,060 --> 00:03:03,940
he had a choice?" Because a confession only means

75
00:03:03,940 --> 00:03:06,680
what we think it means if the person giving

76
00:03:06,680 --> 00:03:09,240
it understood that silence was an option.

77
00:03:10,060 --> 00:03:12,060
In that Phoenix interrogation room,

78
00:03:12,420 --> 00:03:14,960
no one had told Ernesto Miranda that it was.

79
00:03:15,680 --> 00:03:18,040
That confession does not stay in the room.

80
00:03:18,560 --> 00:03:20,460
It becomes evidence in court,

81
00:03:20,460 --> 00:03:22,200
and on the strength of it,

82
00:03:22,660 --> 00:03:23,500
Miranda is convicted.

83
00:03:24,380 --> 00:03:26,740
For most defendants, that would be the end of

84
00:03:26,740 --> 00:03:27,100
the road.

85
00:03:27,800 --> 00:03:30,720
A confession is admitted, a jury hears it,

86
00:03:31,140 --> 00:03:32,100
a verdict follows.

87
00:03:32,740 --> 00:03:34,380
But his case keeps climbing.

88
00:03:35,100 --> 00:03:38,300
The argument on appeal is narrow and sharp: that

89
00:03:38,300 --> 00:03:40,360
the confession should never have counted,

90
00:03:40,720 --> 00:03:43,760
because Miranda was never told the rights that might

91
00:03:43,760 --> 00:03:45,600
have changed whether he spoke at all.

92
00:03:46,280 --> 00:03:48,960
It is not a claim that he was tortured

93
00:03:48,960 --> 00:03:51,900
or tricked in some movie-villain way.

94
00:03:52,800 --> 00:03:54,720
It is something quieter and,

95
00:03:54,720 --> 00:03:56,763
in a sense, more unsettling —

96
00:03:56,980 --> 00:04:00,400
that the ordinary machinery of interrogation can extract

97
00:04:00,400 --> 00:04:03,360
words from a person who does not understand the

98
00:04:03,360 --> 00:04:04,600
ground he is standing on.

99
00:04:05,240 --> 00:04:07,780
And here is the detail most people never learn.

100
00:04:08,640 --> 00:04:11,300
Miranda's case did not travel to the Supreme Court

101
00:04:11,300 --> 00:04:11,680
alone.

102
00:04:12,260 --> 00:04:13,560
By the time it arrived,

103
00:04:13,640 --> 00:04:16,780
it had been combined with three other cases asking

104
00:04:16,780 --> 00:04:19,860
the very same question: Vignera v.

105
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:22,000
New York, Westover v.

106
00:04:22,140 --> 00:04:24,800
United States, and California v.

107
00:04:25,120 --> 00:04:25,400
Stewart.

108
00:04:26,300 --> 00:04:26,900
Four defendants.

109
00:04:27,500 --> 00:04:29,180
Four different interrogation rooms.

110
00:04:29,740 --> 00:04:30,800
One shared problem.

111
00:04:31,440 --> 00:04:33,200
That combination is a signal.

112
00:04:33,880 --> 00:04:37,160
When the Supreme Court pulls four separate cases together

113
00:04:37,160 --> 00:04:40,380
under a single name, it is not trying to

114
00:04:40,380 --> 00:04:42,080
fix one man's bad day.

115
00:04:42,780 --> 00:04:45,368
It is looking at a pattern —

116
00:04:45,369 --> 00:04:48,080
a recurring gap in how the country questions people

117
00:04:48,080 --> 00:04:48,760
in custody.

118
00:04:49,560 --> 00:04:51,340
The justices were not asking,

119
00:04:51,860 --> 00:04:55,360
"was this one confession unfair?" They were asking,

120
00:04:55,700 --> 00:04:57,260
"what should have to be true,

121
00:04:57,260 --> 00:05:00,660
every time, before any of these confessions can be

122
00:05:00,660 --> 00:05:01,320
used at all?"

123
00:05:01,920 --> 00:05:03,960
So the stakes quietly expand.

124
00:05:04,700 --> 00:05:08,420
This stops being the story of Ernesto Miranda and

125
00:05:08,420 --> 00:05:11,760
becomes a question about every locked interrogation room

126
00:05:11,760 --> 00:05:13,145
in the United States —

127
00:05:13,540 --> 00:05:16,540
and about the distance between having a right and

128
00:05:16,540 --> 00:05:18,160
actually knowing you have it.

129
00:05:18,620 --> 00:05:21,680
The Court now has to decide whether the Constitution

130
00:05:21,680 --> 00:05:24,840
demands that someone close that distance out loud,

131
00:05:25,420 --> 00:05:26,740
before the questioning begins.

132
00:05:27,520 --> 00:05:31,060
On June 13, 1966, the Court answers.

133
00:05:31,700 --> 00:05:33,094
By a narrow margin —

134
00:05:33,500 --> 00:05:37,160
five votes to four, with Chief Justice Earl Warren

135
00:05:37,160 --> 00:05:39,465
writing for the majority —

136
00:05:39,466 --> 00:05:42,800
it rules that the prosecution may not use statements

137
00:05:42,800 --> 00:05:46,980
from a custodial interrogation unless it can show the

138
00:05:46,980 --> 00:05:50,140
suspect was first protected by clear safeguards.

139
00:05:51,100 --> 00:05:54,420
And then the Court does something unusual: it spells

140
00:05:54,420 --> 00:05:55,980
the safeguards out.

141
00:05:56,840 --> 00:06:00,560
Before questioning, a person in custody must be told

142
00:06:00,560 --> 00:06:01,260
four things —

143
00:06:02,100 --> 00:06:05,440
that they have the right to remain silent; that

144
00:06:05,440 --> 00:06:08,000
anything they say can be used against them in

145
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:10,720
court; that they have the right to a lawyer;

146
00:06:11,260 --> 00:06:13,340
and that if they cannot afford one,

147
00:06:13,820 --> 00:06:15,880
a lawyer will be appointed for them.

148
00:06:16,760 --> 00:06:19,200
Those four points are the heart of the whole

149
00:06:19,200 --> 00:06:19,680
decision.

150
00:06:20,420 --> 00:06:22,620
They are not a magic script that has to

151
00:06:22,620 --> 00:06:24,806
be read in identical words every time —

152
00:06:25,300 --> 00:06:28,240
they are a floor, a minimum the state has

153
00:06:28,240 --> 00:06:30,800
to clear before a confession can be trusted in

154
00:06:30,800 --> 00:06:31,080
court.

155
00:06:31,820 --> 00:06:34,160
Notice where the Court grounds all of this.

156
00:06:34,780 --> 00:06:36,680
Not in sympathy for suspects,

157
00:06:36,940 --> 00:06:39,071
but in the Fifth Amendment —

158
00:06:39,072 --> 00:06:42,320
the long-standing rule that the government cannot force

159
00:06:42,320 --> 00:06:44,600
you to be a witness against yourself.

160
00:06:45,660 --> 00:06:47,700
The warning, in the Court's reasoning,

161
00:06:47,700 --> 00:06:51,480
is simply what that promise requires once you are

162
00:06:51,480 --> 00:06:53,880
alone in a room with people whose job is

163
00:06:53,880 --> 00:06:54,760
to get you to talk.

164
00:06:55,460 --> 00:06:57,200
It was not a comfortable decision,

165
00:06:57,620 --> 00:06:59,620
and it was not a lopsided one.

166
00:07:00,260 --> 00:07:03,220
Justices Harlan and White each dissented,

167
00:07:03,800 --> 00:07:06,800
arguing that the majority had reached beyond what the

168
00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:09,420
Constitution and earlier cases required,

169
00:07:09,980 --> 00:07:12,480
and warning that the new rule would tie the

170
00:07:12,480 --> 00:07:14,520
hands of legitimate police work.

171
00:07:15,160 --> 00:07:17,460
That disagreement still echoes today.

172
00:07:18,300 --> 00:07:20,820
What happens next is the part you already know

173
00:07:21,881 --> 00:07:22,201
—

174
00:07:22,202 --> 00:07:24,420
you just did not know where it came from.

175
00:07:25,040 --> 00:07:28,300
Almost at once, those four points harden into a

176
00:07:28,300 --> 00:07:29,060
fixed routine.

177
00:07:29,980 --> 00:07:31,380
They get printed on cards,

178
00:07:31,840 --> 00:07:35,080
taped to station walls, and recited at the moment

179
00:07:35,080 --> 00:07:37,240
of arrest until they are nearly automatic.

180
00:07:37,900 --> 00:07:40,300
The country starts calling them by the name of

181
00:07:40,300 --> 00:07:42,540
the case: the Miranda warning.

182
00:07:43,380 --> 00:07:45,440
And this is where the warning reveals what it

183
00:07:45,440 --> 00:07:46,120
really is.

184
00:07:46,640 --> 00:07:48,020
It is not politeness.

185
00:07:48,600 --> 00:07:51,460
It is a small, deliberate transfer of power.

186
00:07:52,460 --> 00:07:54,900
For a few seconds, the closed room is forced

187
00:07:54,900 --> 00:07:57,381
to open —

188
00:07:57,382 --> 00:07:59,740
to admit, out loud, that the person being questioned

189
00:07:59,740 --> 00:08:02,480
has choices: to stay silent,

190
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:04,360
to ask for a lawyer,

191
00:08:04,920 --> 00:08:07,200
to make the state prove its case without his

192
00:08:07,200 --> 00:08:07,560
help.

193
00:08:09,040 --> 00:08:11,820
Power, in that room, had always belonged to whoever

194
00:08:11,820 --> 00:08:15,820
understood the rules; the warning simply hands a piece

195
00:08:15,820 --> 00:08:19,200
of that understanding to the one person who usually

196
00:08:19,200 --> 00:08:20,440
walks in without it.

197
00:08:21,020 --> 00:08:24,140
The warning does not free anyone and does not

198
00:08:24,140 --> 00:08:25,120
end interrogation.

199
00:08:26,080 --> 00:08:29,080
It just refuses to let the room pretend that

200
00:08:29,080 --> 00:08:31,080
the person inside it has no options.

201
00:08:32,080 --> 00:08:33,800
Now the twist promised at the start.

202
00:08:34,560 --> 00:08:37,757
The warning carries Ernesto Miranda's name —

203
00:08:37,758 --> 00:08:39,800
but the ruling did not set him free.

204
00:08:40,540 --> 00:08:43,440
The Supreme Court reversed his original conviction,

205
00:08:43,880 --> 00:08:44,200
yes.

206
00:08:44,940 --> 00:08:46,940
But the state put him on trial a second

207
00:08:46,940 --> 00:08:50,060
time, and at that new trial he was convicted

208
00:08:50,060 --> 00:08:51,840
again, on other evidence.

209
00:08:52,420 --> 00:08:53,300
Sit with that.

210
00:08:54,100 --> 00:08:56,960
The most famous name in American criminal procedure

211
00:08:56,960 --> 00:08:58,580
belongs to a man who,

212
00:08:59,020 --> 00:09:01,460
in the end, was still found guilty.

213
00:09:02,160 --> 00:09:03,460
He did not win his freedom.

214
00:09:04,060 --> 00:09:06,060
He won something stranger and,

215
00:09:06,360 --> 00:09:09,940
for everyone else, far more lasting: a rule.

216
00:09:10,660 --> 00:09:13,360
That is the quiet machinery underneath the phrase.

217
00:09:14,020 --> 00:09:17,360
The Miranda warning is not really about Ernesto Miranda

218
00:09:17,360 --> 00:09:18,020
at all.

219
00:09:18,480 --> 00:09:20,120
It is about the next person,

220
00:09:20,120 --> 00:09:21,043
and the next —

221
00:09:21,640 --> 00:09:24,020
the ones who will sit in that same kind

222
00:09:24,020 --> 00:09:26,920
of room long after his case is closed.

223
00:09:27,640 --> 00:09:30,340
By tying the warning to the Fifth Amendment and

224
00:09:30,340 --> 00:09:32,340
forcing it to be said before questioning,

225
00:09:33,060 --> 00:09:35,700
the Court took a principle that had always existed

226
00:09:35,700 --> 00:09:38,320
on paper and made it show up in the

227
00:09:38,320 --> 00:09:41,660
one place it had been easiest to ignore: the

228
00:09:41,660 --> 00:09:43,880
moment just before someone starts to talk.

229
00:09:44,460 --> 00:09:46,900
So a system that had quietly run on the

230
00:09:46,900 --> 00:09:49,800
gap between having a right and knowing it now

231
00:09:49,800 --> 00:09:51,540
had to close that gap,

232
00:09:51,540 --> 00:09:53,820
out loud, every single time.

233
00:09:54,700 --> 00:09:56,960
Step back and the shape of it is clear.

234
00:09:57,640 --> 00:10:00,200
We started with a sentence that sounds like set

235
00:10:00,200 --> 00:10:01,740
dressing from a crime drama.

236
00:10:02,400 --> 00:10:03,680
It is anything but.

237
00:10:04,920 --> 00:10:08,180
Strip away the television associations and what is left

238
00:10:08,180 --> 00:10:09,496
is structural —

239
00:10:09,760 --> 00:10:12,500
a line drawn around how the state is allowed

240
00:10:12,500 --> 00:10:15,840
to gather the most damning evidence of all: your

241
00:10:15,840 --> 00:10:16,580
own words.

242
00:10:17,340 --> 00:10:20,140
It is a repair the Supreme Court bolted onto

243
00:10:20,140 --> 00:10:22,922
the Fifth Amendment in 1966 —

244
00:10:23,540 --> 00:10:25,608
built out of four plain sentences —

245
00:10:26,060 --> 00:10:28,860
because the room where confessions are made was tilted

246
00:10:28,860 --> 00:10:30,700
against the person inside it.

247
00:10:31,040 --> 00:10:33,480
And the man who gave it its name never

248
00:10:33,480 --> 00:10:35,120
got the ending you would expect.

249
00:10:35,760 --> 00:10:37,940
He won at the highest court in the country

250
00:10:37,940 --> 00:10:39,560
and still went back to prison.

251
00:10:40,260 --> 00:10:42,040
The warning outlived his case,

252
00:10:42,040 --> 00:10:43,980
because it was never really his.

253
00:10:44,710 --> 00:10:46,600
It was a structural fix,

254
00:10:46,600 --> 00:10:49,940
written for everyone who would ever be questioned after

255
00:10:49,940 --> 00:10:50,360
him.

256
00:10:51,160 --> 00:10:54,480
That is the hidden system behind "you have the

257
00:10:54,480 --> 00:10:57,560
right to remain silent": not a courtesy,

258
00:10:57,560 --> 00:11:01,780
but a rule that quietly rebalances every arrest in

259
00:11:01,780 --> 00:11:02,160
America.

260
00:11:03,140 --> 00:11:05,480
If you want to see how a single case

261
00:11:05,480 --> 00:11:08,880
can rewire the country's most ordinary moments,

262
00:11:09,360 --> 00:11:10,853
this channel is built for exactly that —

263
00:11:12,380 --> 00:11:15,360
and the next landmark we open changed who even

264
00:11:15,360 --> 00:11:17,040
gets a lawyer in the first place.

265
00:11:17,760 --> 00:11:20,620
Until then: now you know why they have to

266
00:11:20,620 --> 00:11:21,580
read you your rights.
